[[File:Hermes_3000_typewriter.jpg|thumb|Hermes 3000 typewriter]]
{{short description|Make of typewriter}}
The '''Hermes 3000''' was a lightweight, segment-shifted portable [[typewriter]] manufactured by [[Paillard-Bolex]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YDMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15|title=Hermes|work=The Rotarian|date=July 1968|p=15}}</ref><ref name="Polt20152">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhXSBgAAQBAJ|title=The Typewriter Revolution: A Typist's Companion for the 21st Century|author=Richard Polt|date=12 November 2015|publisher=Countryman Press|isbn=978-1-58157-587-3}}</ref> "Bulbous" and "angular" in shape,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uhXSBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=snippet&q=hermes%203000&f=false|title=The Typewriter Revolution: A Typist's Companion for the 21st Century|last=Polt|first=Richard|date=2015-11-12|publisher=The Countryman Press|isbn=9781581575873|language=en}}</ref> it came with a fitted, hard-shell removable cover. The machines were built in [[Yverdon]], [[Switzerland]] by Paillard S.A.<ref name="Breiding2013">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mnkYFt6pijoC|title=Swiss Made: The Untold Story Behind Switzerland's Success|author=R. James Breiding|date=10 January 2013|publisher=Profile Books|isbn=1-84765-809-1}}</ref>

The model was introduced in 1958<ref name=":0" /> as a successor to the [[Hermes 2000]].<ref name="Polt20152" /> Its original iteration, the ''Model 1'', was produced until 1966. With subsequent design modifications to the external casing and a variety of subtle changes in colour finishes, the Hermes 3000 was manufactured into the 1980's.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://typewriters.ch/collection/hermes_3000.html|title=Hermes 3000  typewriter|website=typewriters.ch}}</ref> Although it was a portable machine the Hermes 3000 had a few deluxe features, such as a "beyond the margins" key and a separate key that could be depressed to free any jammed keys and return them to their resting position.<ref>{{cite document|title=How your Hermes 3000 Works|publisher=Hermes|p=7|url=http://site.xavier.edu/polt/typewriters/hermes3000.pdf|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> They predominently came in a light green (occasionally described as a mint<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finebooksmagazine.com/fine_books_blog/2018/02/|title=The Fine Books Blog: February 2018 Archives|website=www.finebooksmagazine.com|access-date=2018-12-01}}</ref> or"sea-foam green") colour.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uhXSBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=snippet&q=hermes%203000&f=false|title=The Typewriter Revolution: A Typist's Companion for the 21st Century|last=Polt|first=Richard|date=2015-11-12|publisher=The Countryman Press|isbn=9781581575873|language=en}}</ref>
== In popular culture ==
{{Quotebox|quote="Most heartfelt, I thank my typewriter. My typewriter is a Hermes 3000, surely one of the noblest instruments of European genius. It has kept me for thirty years out of the dry embrace of the computer".<ref name="Polt2015">{{cite book|author=Richard Polt|title=The Typewriter Revolution: A Typist's Companion for the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhXSBgAAQBAJ|date=12 November 2015|publisher=Countryman Press|isbn=978-1-58157-587-3}}</ref>|source=[[Larry McMurtry]] at the Golden Globe Awards|width=35em|salign=left|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|qalign=center|align=left}}[[William Kotzwinkle]]'s 1972 novel was named ''Hermes 3000'' after the machine.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=97-wAAAAIAAJ&q=%22hermes+3000%22&dq=%22hermes+3000%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDvqXC9P7eAhViJcAKHbfzA48Q6AEIKjAA|title=Hermes 3000|last=Kotzwinkle|first=William|date=1972|publisher=Pantheon Books|isbn=9780394476216|language=en}}</ref> During his acceptance speech for "Best Screenplay ([[Brokeback Mountain]])" at the [[2006 Golden Globes]], author [[Larry McMurtry]] specifically mentioned his Hermes 3000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2006-01-20-0601190365-story.html|title=What's so special about a Hermes 3000?|first=Julia Keller, Tribune cultural critic. Additional reporting by Robert K.|last=Elder|publisher=}}</ref> Other notable users of the machine are [[Sam Shepard]], [[Eugène Ionesco]] and [[Stephen Fry]].<ref name="Polt20152"/> [[Beat Generation|Beat writer]] [[Jack Kerouac]] wrote his final novel, ''[[Vanity of Duluoz]]'',<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/21/style/sylvia-plath-auction-bonhams-frieda-hughes.html|title=Who Bought Sylvia Plath’s Stuff?|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en}}</ref> on the Hermes 3000 in 1966. In a March 2018 [[auction]] at [[Bonhams]] in London, the Hermes 3000 on which [[Sylvia Plath]] had typed her only novel—''[[The Bell Jar]]''—in 1962 was sold for £26,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2018/mar/22/is-sylvia-plaths-drivers-license-worth-more-than-a-letter-from-dickens|title=Is Sylvia Plath's driver's license worth more than a letter from Dickens?|last=Dugdale|first=John|date=2018-03-22|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-12-01}}</ref> ($46,071)<ref name="auto"/>{{Refn|Described in ''[[The Financial Times]]'' as "a mint-green Hermes 3000 typewriter, lightly smudged, bought in Boston in 1959",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9ac1e3b4-319f-11e8-ac48-10c6fdc22f03|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' later noted that the Bonhams' sale placed the value of Plath's Hermes "comfortably above Jack Kerouac’s, also a green Hermes, which pulled in $22,500 (£16,000), and John Updike’s $4,375 (£3,110)".|group=note}} in 2013, in an appearance on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', actor [[Tom Hanks]] named the Hermes 3000 as the luxury he would choose to take with him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/tom-hankss-typewriter-stories-reveal-inventive-mind-uncommon/|title=Tom Hanks's typewriter stories reveal his inventive mind – Uncommon Type, review|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=2017-10-15|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>{{Refn|Hanks has been described as a "connoisseur" of typewriters, possessing 250 of the machines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/tom-hankss-typewriter-stories-reveal-inventive-mind-uncommon/|title=Tom Hanks's typewriter stories reveal his inventive mind – Uncommon Type, review|first=Helen|last=Brown|date=15 October 2017|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> In a 2013 [[opinion piece]] for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Hanks described the Hermes range as the "“The Cadillac of typewriters”.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/04/opinion/sunday/i-am-tom-i-like-to-type-hear-that.html|title=Opinion - I Am TOM. I Like to TYPE. Hear That?|publisher=}}</ref>|group=note}}

